\cf2 A massive {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://annals.org/aim/article/doi/10.7326/M18-2101"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 new study from Denmark}} found no association between being vaccinated against measles, mumps, and rubella and developing autism.\
In science and public health circles, that issue has long since been considered settled, with multiple studies over many years discounting the findings of a small study published more than 20 years ago that has since been expunged from the medical literature.\
But the size of this study \'97 involving 657,461 Danish children born between 1999 and 2010 \'97 should, in theory, bolster the argument that doctors and public health professionals still find themselves forced to make in the face of entrenched and growing resistance to vaccination in some quarters.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The work, published Monday in the Annals of Internal Medicine, was conducted by researchers at the Statens Serum Institut in Copenhagen. Some of the same scientists published an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa021134?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&rfr_dat=cr_pub%3dwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 earlier article}} on this topic in the New England Journal of Medicine in 2002, based on data from 537,303 Danish children born between 1991 and 1998.
