\cf2 He also wrote that evidence hasn\'92t won over the skeptics so far. \'93It has been said that we now live in a \'91fact-resistant\'92 world where data have limited persuasive value,\'94 he said.\
But Hviid said the size of this study allowed his group to look at some additional claims that are made about MMR vaccine \'97 for example that children considered \'93at risk\'94 of developing autism might be more likely to be diagnosed with the condition if they receive the vaccine. That argument is sometimes made about children who have a sibling with autism.\
The Danish data, drawn from a national health registry, showed no increase in autism in this subset of children. Nor did it see an onset of autism symptoms clustered around the timing of the MMR vaccine receipt.\
\'93We found no support for the hypothesis of increased risk for autism after MMR vaccination in \'85 Danish children; no support for the hypothesis of MMR vaccination triggering autism in susceptible subgroups characterized by environmental and familial risk factors; and no support for a clustering of autism cases in specific time periods after MMR vaccination,\'94 Hviid and his co-authors wrote.\
Omer said the focus now needs to be on studies that make clear how best to persuade vaccine-hesitant parents that the vaccines are safe and in their children\'92s best interest. Progress is being made on figuring out how to effectively communicate with such parents, he said, noting they make up a larger group than the more vocal individuals who flatly reject vaccines.\
\'93It\'92s an active area of research. But there are a lot of promising techniques that are coming online,\'94 Omer said.\
